{{more citations needed|date=May 2018}}

'''Najm al‐Dīn al‐Miṣrī''' ({{lang-ar|نجم الدين المصري}}) was a 13th-century Egyptian [[Islamic astronomer|astronomer]] mostly known for writing a large astronomical table that had nearly 415,000 entries. The table is considered to be the largest of its kind ever produced by one person during the [[Middle Ages]]. Although the main purpose of the work was astronomical timekeeping, it can also be used to solve all problems of [[spherical trigonometry]] by changing the arguments of the table.<ref>{{cite web|title=Najm al-Din al-Misri|url=http://islamsci.mcgill.ca/RASI/BEA/Najm_al-Din_al-Misri_BEA.htm|website=islamsci.mcgill.ca}}</ref>

Najm al‐Din also wrote an important illustrated treatise that describes more than 100 different astronomical instruments, including ones he invented himself. This work is of high importance for modern scholars and one of the main sources on the subject.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Selin|first1=Helaine|title=Encyclopaedia of the History of Science, Technology, and Medicine in Non-Western Cultures|date=2008|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781402045592|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=kt9DIY1g9HYC&pg=PA275&dq=%22Najm+al%E2%80%90Din+al%E2%80%90misri%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic172f3P_aAhXB1xQKHTGZBCI4ChDoAQguMAI#v=onepage&q=%22Najm%20al%E2%80%90Din%22%20%22cairo%20astronomer%22&f=false|language=en}}</ref>

