'''The unsuccessful self-treatment of a case of "writer's block"''' is a [[humor]]ous [[academic article]] by psychologist Dennis Upper about [[writer's block]]. It contains no content outside title and journal formatting elements, including a humorous footnote. Published in 1974 in a peer reviewed journal, ''[[Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis]]'', it is recognized as the shortest academic article ever<ref name=realclearscience>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearscience.com/blog/2014/01/shortest_science_papers.html|title=The Shortest Science Paper Ever Published Had No Words, and Was Utterly Brilliant - RealClearScience|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> and a classic example of humour in science,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arnosimons.com/2013/06/20/humor-in-science-episode-1-writers-block/|title=Humor in Science (Episode 1: Writer’s Block) - arno simons|work=arno simons|accessdate=6 October 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006112103/http://arnosimons.com/2013/06/20/humor-in-science-episode-1-writers-block/|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=}}</ref> or at the very least among [[behavioral psychology|behavioral psychologists]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bassett|first1=John E.|title=Perspectives in Behavior Therapy (Book)|journal=Journal of Personality Assessment|volume=43|issue=1|pages=105–105|doi=10.1207/s15327752jpa4301_20|year=2010}}</ref> It has been cited at least 60 times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cites=12780192540682800595&as_sdt=2005&sciodt=0,5|title=Google Scholar|website=scholar.google.com}}</ref>
The article received a humorous positive review which was published alongside the article.<ref name=realclearscience/>
{{cquote|I have studied this manuscript very carefully with lemon juice and X-rays and have not detected a single flaw in either design or writing style. I suggest it be published without revision. Clearly it is the most concise manuscript I have ever seen-yet it contains sufficient detail to allow other investigators to replicate Dr. Upper's failure. In comparison with the other manuscripts I get from you containing all that complicated detail, this one was a pleasure to examine. Surely we can find a place for this paper in the Journal-perhaps on the edge of a blank page.}}
The article has led to at least three similarly humorous and peer-reviewed, published replication studies,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Molloy|first1=Geoffery N.|title=THE UNSUCCESSFUL SELF-TREATMENT OF A CASE OF "WRITER'S BLOCK": A REPLICATION|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|volume=57|issue=2|pages=566–566|doi=10.2466/pms.1983.57.2.566|year=1983}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Didden|first1=Robert|last2=Sigafoos|first2=Jeff|last3=O'Reilly|first3=Mark F|last4=Lancioni|first4=Giulio E|last5=Sturmey|first5=Peter|last6=LeBlanc|first6=Linda|title=A Multisite Cross-Cultural Replication of Upper's (1974) Unsuccessful Self-Treatment of Writer's Block|journal=Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis|volume=40|issue=4|pages=773–773|doi=10.1901/jaba.2007.773|year=2007|pmc=2078566}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=HERMANN|first1=BRUCE P.|title=UNSUCCESSFUL SELF-TREATMENT OF A CASE OF 'WRITER'S BLOCK': A PARTIAL FAILURE TO REPLICATE|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|volume=58|issue=2|pages=350–350|doi=10.2466/pms.1984.58.2.350|year=2016}}</ref> and several similar papers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mclean|first1=Derrick C.|last2=Thomas|first2=Benjamin R.|title=UNSUCCESSFUL TREATMENTS OF "WRITER'S BLOCK": A META-ANALYSIS|journal=Psychological Reports|volume=115|issue=1|pages=276–278|doi=10.2466/28.PR0.115c12z0|year=2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=SKINNER|first1=NICHOLAS F.|last2=PERLINI|first2=ARTHUR H.|title=THE UNSUCCESSFUL GROUP TREATMENT OF 'WRITER'S BLOCK': A TEN-YEAR FOLLOW-UP|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|volume=82|issue=1|pages=138–138|doi=10.2466/pms.1996.82.1.138|year=2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=SKINNER|first1=NICHOLAS F.|last2=PERLINI|first2=ARTHUR H.|last3=FRIC|first3=LAWRENCE|last4=WERSTINE|first4=E. PAUL|last5=CALLA|first5=JAMES|title=THE UNSUCCESSFUL GROUP-TREATMENT OF "WRITER'S BLOCK"|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|volume=61|issue=1|pages=298–298|doi=10.2466/pms.1985.61.1.298|year=2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=OLSON|first1=KENNETH R.|title=UNSUCCESSFUL SELF-TREATMENT OF 'WRITER'S BLOCK': A REVIEW OF THE LITERATURE|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|volume=59|issue=1|pages=158–158|doi=10.2466/pms.1984.59.1.158|year=2016}}</ref>
More seriously, the paper is said to be a case reinforcing the image of a writer's block as a "blank page",<ref name="Carter2007">{{cite book|author=Geoffrey Vincent Carter|title=Rereading and Rewriting Bloc/ks: Teaching Multi-modal Literacies Through an Apprenticeship in Proper Names|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qZRe4quXR1oC&pg=PA3|year=2007|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-549-30355-8|page=3}}</ref> and encouraging brevity in writing.<ref name="Glasser2014">{{cite book|author=Stephen P. Glasser|title=Essentials of Clinical Research|year=2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-05470-4|pages=415–416}}</ref> It has been also used as an example that humor can indeed be found in academic publishing.<ref name="FrySalameh1987">{{cite book|author1=William F. Fry|author2=Waleed A. Salameh|title=Handbook of humor and psychotherapy: advances in the clinical use of humor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cyXtZvVq34AC|date=December 1987|publisher=Professional Resource Exchange|isbn=978-0-943158-19-8|page=150}}</ref>
